				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ {C}_2{H}_5 OH+{CO}_2\to 3 CO+3{H}_2 $$\end{document}

Partial oxidation is another reforming technology to convert the oxygenated hydrocarbons into hydrogen and CO2 or syngas. In this reforming technology, the reaction is exothermic in nature, where it is not required to provide external heating other than the supply of air or pure oxygen. Complete oxidation (air supply in excess) will burn the fuel or reactant completely, hence reducing the amount of hydrogen produced. Therefore, the amount of air or oxygen supplied may need to be carefully controlled to yield optimum products. The stoichiometric equation of partial oxidation is as follows and applies to all oxygenates:28CxHyOz+2x−z2O2→xCO2+y2H2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
